{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 16:12:38.554905", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi-tier EBGP Clos\n\nSummary\n- Overall control-plane (EBGP) appears healthy: BGP adjacencies and inter-router routes are present across leaves, spines, and super-spine.\n- Data-plane reachability is mostly OK except for host pc_0_1, which shows severe packet loss when talking to other subnets.\n- Root-cause evidence points to a host-local traffic-control impairment on pc_0_1: a netem qdisc configured with 60% packet corruption on pc_0_1:eth0. This explains the observed high packet loss / failures originating from that host.\n\nWhat I ran / checked\n- Global reachability probe (get_reachability) across hosts.\n- FRR running-config and routing table (show running-config, show ip route) on all FRR routers: leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, super_spine_router_0.\n- Targeted ping from pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0.\n- Host network configuration for pc_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1 (ifconfig / ip addr / ip route).\n- tc statistics for pc_0_1:eth0.\n\nKey test results and relevant evidence\n- Reachability summary (selected):\n  - Many pc -> pc pings returned OK with low RTTs (examples in global probe).\n  - Entries for pc_0_1 -> others were reported as \"unknown\" in the global probe (suspicious).\n- Direct ping test:\n  - ping from pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0: 4 transmitted, 1 received, 75% packet loss\n    - Output: \"4 packets transmitted, 1 received, 75% packet loss, rtt min/avg/max/mdev = 2.562/2.562/2.562/0.000 ms\"\n- pc_0_1 network config:\n  - pc_0_1 eth0 = 10.0.1.2/24; default via 10.0.1.1 (leaf_router_0_1)\n  - ifconfig counters show low packet counts (TX 13, RX 6).\n- tc statistics (pc_0_1:eth0):\n  - qdisc netem 8066: root ... corrupt 60%\n  - \"Sent 994 bytes 13 pkt ... corrupt 60%\"\n  - This indicates netem is configured to corrupt ~60% of packets on the host interface.\n- leaf_router_0_1 (the leaf for 10.0.1.0/24):\n  - Interface eth4 = 10.0.1.1/24 (connected to pc_0_1).\n  - Kernel route: 10.0.1.0/24 dev eth4 (local).\n  - BGP: leaf_router_0_1 is advertising 10.0.1.0/24 and has expected EBGP neighbors configured.\n  - Routes to other pods/networks are present via neighbors — control-plane correct.\n\nControl-plane / routing health\n- leaf_router_0_0 and leaf_router_0_1 FRR configs show proper BGP process and network statements for their directly-connected /24 host subnets.\n- spine and super-spine routers show routes to the 10.0.x/24 and 10.1.x/24 networks via the expected next-hops.\n- No missing route entries or incorrect next-hops were observed in the routers’ routing tables. This supports that BGP route propagation is functioning.\n\nAnomalies and localization\n- Symptom: high packet loss (75% measured) and inability of pc_0_1 to reach other hosts reliably.\n- Localized to: pc_0_1 (host interface eth0) and its L2/L3 edge with leaf_router_0_1 (leaf eth4 is the default gateway).\n- Direct evidence localizing the fault:\n  - pc_0_1 tc shows \"corrupt 60%\".\n  - ping from pc_0_1 to pc_0_0: heavy packet loss.\n  - Leaf router shows subnet and routes are present and BGP is up, indicating the underlay and control-plane are not the primary cause.\n\nRoot-cause analysis (concise)\n- The most likely root cause is host-local packet corruption injected by the netem qdisc on pc_0_1:eth0 (corrupt 60%). This causes a high fraction of packets to be corrupted and likely dropped by endpoints or intermediate stacks, resulting in effective packet loss and degraded reachability from that host.\n- Corroborating evidence: working BGP and routing across the fabric; local host tc shows corruption; failing pings originate from that host. The fabric (leaf/spine/super-spine) has correct routes to 10.0.1.0/24 and the leaf’s interface is up.\n\nOther observations / notes\n- Packet counters on pc_0_1 are low; this may indicate limited traffic volume during tests or retransmissions. The combination of netem corruption and low packet counts makes loss percentage measurements more variable (observed 60% corrupt vs 75% ping loss — expected variation because corrupted packets may be dropped or not counted as successful ping replies).\n- No signs of BGP flaps or missing inter-router adjacencies in the router outputs collected.\n- No evidence of link-state failures on router interfaces; all inter-router /31 links show directly connected entries.\n\nConclusion\n- Network control-plane and inter-router forwarding appear healthy.\n- The major data-plane anomaly is confined to host pc_0_1; root cause is the host-local netem qdisc configured to corrupt 60% of packets on pc_0_1:eth0, causing high packet loss and reachability issues for that host.\n\nIf you want, I can (only upon explicit request) gather additional low-level packet traces (tcpdump), show the full tc qdisc configuration commands on pc_0_1, or check neighbor adjacency states on FRR to further confirm timing or BGP update activity.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 11559, "output_tokens": 2121, "total_tokens": 13680, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 10752}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 832}}}
